Concatenating two UC_STRING values whose combined lengths equal or exceed
SIZE_MAX caused a size_t integer overflow in uc_vm_string_concat(). The
original guard used > instead of >=, so the l1 + l2 == SIZE_MAX case
passed through: the subsequent l1 + l2 + 1 expression wraps to 0, which
is less than sizeof(buf) (8 on 64-bit), causing the code to take the
stack-buffer memcpy branch and overflow an 8-byte buffer with SIZE_MAX
bytes of data.

The fix changes the guard to >= (via uc_string_concat_would_overflow())
and raises a Runtime error exception so the condition is surfaced to
script-level try/catch or terminates the script with a readable error
message rather than silently pushing null onto the VM stack.

The overflow guard logic is unit-tested in
tests/unit/test_string_concat_overflow.c using contrived SIZE_MAX-boundary
values without requiring real gigabyte allocations.
